Yes 👍 — you can forward email from a domain registered in AWS to your personal email, even if your site is just static HTML. The website hosting doesn’t matter because email is controlled by DNS (MX records), not your web backend.

There are three common approaches, from easiest to most “AWS-native”.

1️⃣ Easiest: Use a simple email forwarding service (recommended)

This is what most people with static sites do.

Services like:

ImprovMX (free tier)

ForwardMX

SimpleLogin

Mailgun routes

You just point your domain’s MX records to them.

Example flow:

Sign up for ImprovMX

Add your domain

Configure forwarding rule
hello@yourdomain.com → you@gmail.com

Change MX records in Route53

Example MX records:

MX 10 mx1.improvmx.com
MX 20 mx2.improvmx.com

Done. Emails sent to your domain get forwarded.

This takes 5 minutes and avoids running infrastructure.

2️⃣ AWS-only solution (SES + S3 + Lambda)

If you want to stay entirely in AWS:

Architecture:

Email → SES → S3 → Lambda → forward to Gmail

Steps:

Verify your domain in Amazon SES

Add MX record:

MX 10 inbound-smtp.<region>.amazonaws.com

SES receives email

Email stored in S3

Lambda forwards email to your personal address

SES handles incoming mail using DNS MX records and can trigger Lambda to process it.

Pros:

extremely cheap (usually pennies)

flexible (different addresses → different destinations)

Cons:

more setup

requires Lambda code

3️⃣ Paid email hosting (Google Workspace / Fastmail / Zoho)

If you want actual inboxes on your domain.

Example:

you@yourdomain.com
contact@yourdomain.com

Providers:

Google Workspace

Fastmail

Zoho Mail

Cost: ~$3–6/month.

